Ms. Bianchi and Ms. Morrison walked into the grocery store at the same time, and, after a moment of mutual recognition, greeted each other with a handshake.

0.33: They were standing in the entrance of the grocery store, which had displays of pumpkins, candy, and halloween decorations set up in different stations around the door. 

0.67*: “Thank you again for inviting me here to discuss my business proposal,” said Ms. Bianchi.

0.04: “It’s a pleasure to be out of the office.” 

0.42: As an account representative for an Italian cheese company that was trying to expand its outreach to American grocery stores, this meeting was pivotal for Ms. Bianchi.

0.21: Her sales target, Ms. Morrison, was the senior purchasing manager for a corporate grocer and she had a say in the products distributed in stores across the West Coast.

0.38: Ms. Morrison was also known for doing things unconventionally: for example, she said that she liked to make deals with suppliers in the place where the products were sold- “to keep their minds focused on what’s important.” 

****** LOCATION BOUNDARY ******

0.5*: In the cheese section of the grocery store, Ms. Morrison motioned to the parmesan.

0.12: “We have quite a selection here.

0.12: I don’t know that we need an additional section for gourmet cheeses.” 

****** SOCIAL BOUNDARY ******

0.38: Ms. Bianchi did not hesitate but launched into her pitch: “Ms. Morrison, I think you would agree that selling food is not just about providing variety, but also about providing the highest quality.

0.0: You don’t have cheeses made in America that are like ours- it is true.

0.12: The availability of a product of excellent quality leads to the appreciation of the product.

0.08: Your consumers will want to buy other, finer products to compliment that first ingredient, and suddenly your customer will be consuming in a new, more profitable way.

0.21: I propose that you give it a shot: buy $1500 worth of cheese products for a few stores, and see how the sales increase not only in our cheeses, but also in products related to cheeses like crackers, jams, and olives.”

0.33: Ms. Bianchi picked up a box of crackers by the cheese section, and said, “Here, I will buy these, and we can try some of our cheeses that I've brought with me.”

0.12: Ms. Morrison, who was thinking about the proposed offer, nodded in agreement and said, “That sounds like a great idea, but those crackers are on me.”

0.17: She took the crackers from Ms. Bianchi and also picked up a bottle of ketchup and a case of sparkling water “for later.”

****** LOCATION BOUNDARY ******

0.75*: It was very busy in the checkout area.

0.08: People were stocking up for Halloween parties and trick-or-treating, and there were 10 aisles open. 

0.08: They stepped into lane 6 and waited.

0.67*: Ms. Bianchi handed to Ms. Morrison a packet with printed graphs of the increase in profits that several other stores in Italy had seen after starting to carry their products.

****** SOCIAL BOUNDARY ******

0.17: After a couple minutes of thinking, Ms. Morrison widened her eyes and said confidently, “You know what, I think this could work. 

0.04: We've been trying to find a way to add a little European cachet to our stores.

0.04: Our competitor, Orange Grocers, hasn’t expanded in this direction yet, and I’d like to beat them to it. 

0.25: There's still a problem though- I'm worried we'll be paying out the nose for the import taxes.

****** LOCATION BOUNDARY ******

0.58*: It was Ms. Morrison’s turn to check out, and the cashier chatted with Ms. Morrison as she scanned the items.

0.25: Ms. Morrison was also distinguished for knowing most of the employees personally. 

0.25: Ms. Bianchi watched in amusement as Ms. Morrison paid the $23 price by writing a check. 

****** SOCIAL BOUNDARY ******

0.62*: After Ms. Bianci addressed Ms. Morrison’s concerns, they came to an agreement and would have enough cheese shipments, $20,000 worth, to different stores to qualify for a subsidized import tax. 

0.33: Ms. Morrison had had a small bottle of champagne in her purse, and she pulled it out and popped it in celebration of their deal. 

0.21: Ms. Bianchi decided that she loved doing business with Americans. 

